GateDocument.TextWithNodes: * * * * CALL FOR PAPERS * * * * Workshop on Technologies for E-S ervices September 14 and 15 , 2000 Hotel Le Meridien Pyramids Cairo , Egypt http : / / www . hpl . hp . com / hosted / tes 2000 In cooperation with VLDB 2000 Paper submission deadline : May 5 , 2000 * * Selected papers will be proposed for publication in a forthcoming special issue of the VLDB journal GOALS OF THE WORKSHOP The Web is changing every aspect of our lives , but no area is undergoing as rapid and significant changes as the way businesses operate . Today , large and small companies are using the Web to communicate with their partners , to connect with their back-end systems , and to perform electronic commerce transactions . The next chapter of the Internet story is the evolution of today 's e-business and e-commerce systems into "e-services", such as order procurement , on-line trading , customer relationship management , product promotion , or real-time car navigation and traffic information services . In order to make e-services available to customers , service providers need to address several issues , such as : e-service description : which are the attributes of an e-service that should be made visible to customers or applications , and how they should be described . e-service advertisement : how service providers can publish service descriptions so that they can be discovered and accessed by customers and applications . e-service discovery and selection : how customers and applications can discover and select the e-service ( or the combination of e-services ) that best fulfill their requirements . e-service composition : how basic e-services ( possibly offered by different companies ) can be combined to form value-added services . Which architectures , models , and languages can achieve zero latency service integration and cross-organizational business process automation . e-service delivery : how e-services are delivered to businesses and customers . e-service monitoring and analysis : how service executions can be monitored and how service execution data can be analyzed in order to improve the service quality or efficiency . e-service contracts : how to electronically agree on and perform legal contracts between service providers and clients . e-service ratings : how to validate service claims and evaluate the quality of the different service providers . The goal of this workshop is to identify the technical issues and the infrastructures that enable organizations to provide e-services to businesses and customers . The workshop aims at bringing together researchers and developers working in the areas of e-commerce , Web portals , application servers , ontology , description languages , and process management systems . RELEVANT TOPICS Authors are invited to submit research papers as well as reports on work in progress related to one or more of the following topics : Business data exchange format and standards E- service business models E- business process management Enterprise application integration to support service delivery Interorganizational workflows On-line auctions Pricing and payment models Process knowledge management Query languages for e-service discovery and selection Resource management Service advertisement Service agreements and legal contracts Service brokering and optimized service selection Service composition Service description languages and ontology Service invocation protocols Service monitoring and management Service personalization Service rating models Security in service discovery and delivery Standards for e-commerce and e-services Technologies and infrastructures for e-commerce Web portals and application servers Web-based information systems Workflow management support for e-service delivery SUBMISSION GUIDELINES Papers should not exceed 20 double-spaced pages ( including title page , figures and references ) with font not smaller than 11 points .
